<Layout title="Module 1 – Introduction to Nursing & Safety">
  <h1>Module 1: Introduction to Nursing &amp; Safety</h1>

  <h2>Nursing Roles &amp; Scope of Practice</h2>
  <p>
    Nurses practice within a legally defined <strong>scope of practice</strong> established
    by state nurse practice acts. Understanding boundaries is essential to safe, ethical care.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>RN:</strong> Assess, plan, implement, and evaluate patient care; delegate tasks.</li>
    <li><strong>LPN/LVN:</strong> Collect data, perform procedures, administer medications (varies by state).</li>
    <li><strong>CNA/NAP:</strong> Assist with activities of daily living (ADLs) under RN supervision.</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="tip">
    <strong>💡 Key Concept</strong>
    Delegation requires the nurse to assess the patient's condition, the task's complexity,
    the unlicensed personnel's competency, and available supervision. Use the <em>Five Rights
    of Delegation</em>: Right Task, Right Circumstance, Right Person, Right Direction, Right
    Supervision.
  </div>

  <h2>Patient Safety &amp; Error Prevention</h2>
  <p>
    Patient safety is a core nursing responsibility. The <strong>Quality and Safety Education
    for Nurses (QSEN)</strong> framework identifies six competencies: patient-centered care,
    teamwork and collaboration, evidence-based practice, quality improvement, safety, and
    informatics.
  </p>
  <h3>Common Error-Prevention Strategies</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Use two patient identifiers before every procedure (name + date of birth or medical record number).</li>
    <li>Perform hand-offs using structured communication tools (e.g., <strong>SBAR</strong>).</li>
    <li>Apply fall-risk assessment tools and implement individualized prevention plans.</li>
    <li>Report near-misses and adverse events through the facility's incident reporting system.</li>
    <li>Follow alarm management protocols to reduce alarm fatigue.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Infection Control &amp; Hand Hygiene</h2>
  <p>
    Healthcare-associated infections (HAIs) are largely preventable. Hand hygiene is the
    single most effective measure to prevent HAIs.
  </p>
  <h3>Hand Hygiene Guidelines (CDC / WHO)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Wash with soap and water for at least 20 seconds when hands are visibly soiled or after caring for a patient with <em>Clostridioides difficile</em>.</li>
    <li>Use alcohol-based hand rub (ABHR) for all other clinical indications.</li>
    <li>Perform hand hygiene before touching a patient, before clean/aseptic procedures, after body-fluid exposure, after touching a patient, and after touching patient surroundings (WHO 5 Moments).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Precautions &amp; Isolation</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Type</th>
        <th>Route of Transmission</th>
        <th>PPE Required</th>
        <th>Example Pathogens</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Standard</strong></td>
        <td>Blood, body fluids, non-intact skin</td>
        <td>Gloves; mask/gown/goggles if splash risk</td>
        <td>All patients</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Contact</strong></td>
        <td>Direct / indirect contact</td>
        <td>Gloves &amp; gown</td>
        <td>MRSA, VRE, C. diff, scabies</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Droplet</strong></td>
        <td>Respiratory droplets &gt; 5 µm</td>
        <td>Surgical mask (within 3 ft), eye protection</td>
        <td>Influenza, pertussis, meningitis</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Airborne</strong></td>
        <td>Droplet nuclei ≤ 5 µm</td>
        <td>N95 respirator, negative-pressure room</td>
        <td>TB, measles, varicella</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="warning">
    <strong>⚠️ Remember</strong>
    Always don PPE before entering the room and doff carefully to avoid self-contamination.
    Remove gloves first, perform hand hygiene, then remove gown, mask, and goggles in the
    correct sequence.
  </div>

  <h2>Key Terms</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>HAI:</strong> Healthcare-associated infection.</li>
    <li><strong>SBAR:</strong> Situation, Background, Assessment, Recommendation — structured communication tool.</li>
    <li><strong>PPE:</strong> Personal protective equipment.</li>
    <li><strong>QSEN:</strong> Quality and Safety Education for Nurses.</li>
    <li><strong>Scope of practice:</strong> Legal boundaries within which a healthcare professional may work.</li>
  </ul>
</Layout>
